## SECTION 1: THE PROBLEM

### The 11+ isn't testing what you think it's testing.

Most parents assume the 11+ tests whether a child knows the material. It does — but that's not what separates the children who finish from the children who don't.

The exam is designed around time. The papers are written so that a child who can identify what a question is asking within the first sentence — before reading the numbers, before building up a full picture of the problem — will have enough time to complete every question and check their answers.

A child who reads each question fully before selecting a method will often not finish. Not because they don't understand it. Because their reading process takes longer, every single time, across every question on the paper.

The gap isn't knowledge. It's the first three seconds of every question.

