## SECTION 2: TWO TYPES OF READER

### Watch what happens in the first few seconds.

Give two equally capable children the same question. One glances at the opening line and a method fires immediately — almost automatic. The other reads the whole thing carefully, builds up a clear picture of what's being asked, selects the method, and solves it.

Same answer. Same understanding. But consistently different speeds — and under exam conditions, that difference compounds across 50 questions.

The first child has a fast classification reflex. They've seen enough questions that the opening language triggers the method before conscious deliberation kicks in.

The second child constructs first, then solves. Their understanding is often deeper — they rarely make the overconfident errors that catch the first child on unfamiliar questions. But in a timed exam, construction takes time that the format doesn't give them.

**This is the child who confuses their parents and tutors. Clearly capable. Clearly trying. Scores not reflecting ability.**

And the standard response — more practice — almost never fixes it. More practice produces more of the same careful, correct, slow derivations.

